article.headline: Sting open with wins over WNBA's top teams
article.linkText: Sting prove opener no fluke by beating Comets
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- The Charlotte Sting are determined not to
put themselves in the same big hole they started in last season.

	   The Sting, who began last year 1-10 before rallying to win the
Eastern Conference, moved to 2-0 by beating the Houston Comets
67-52 on Monday night.

	   It was the second-straight win over a Western Conference
heavyweight -- Charlotte beat the defending WNBA champion Los
Angeles Sparks in the season opener.

	   ``We're pretty excited about the start -- not just 2-0 but 2-0
against two very good teams,'' coach Anne Donovan said. ``The wins
give us tremendous confidence and it's going to be imperative that
no matter who we play, we remain focused.''

	   Charlotte was swept by Los Angeles in the WNBA Finals last year,
then got slight revenge Saturday night by beating the Sparks in
overtime.

	   The Sting then proved that win was no fluke by beating the
Comets, winners of the first four WNBA titles before the Sparks
knocked them off last season.

	   ``I think the rest of the league is definitely paying
attention,'' said guard Andrea Stinson, who led the Sting with 23
points.

	   ``We have been playing hard since the end of last year and
proved it with a pair of wins over two very big teams in this
league.''

	   Stinson was a game-time decision after spraining her ankle in
the opener. She was on the floor at tipoff, keeping intact her
streak of playing in all of the Sting's 155 regular-season games in
league history. Stinson is one of three players not to miss a game
since the WNBA started in 1997.

	   She showed no lingering effects of the sprain, hitting eight of
her nine shots -- four were 3-pointers -- and adding six rebounds and
four assists.

	   ``Sure it hurts, I sprained it 48 hours ago,'' Stinson said.
``But I'm just a player who loves to play, and when I get on the
floor, I kind of block it out.''

	   Stinson teamed with Dawn Staley to score 27 points in the second
half on 9-of-12 shooting.

	   ``Andrea would tell you she was 100 percent, but she is not full
strength,'' Donovan said. ``It's just veteran players like Andrea
and Dawn that understand how to play through pain and understand
how to do all the things off the floor to get themselves back on
the floor.''

	   Staley finished with 14 points and seven assists for the Sting,
who have only recently been successful against Western Conference
teams. The Comets had beaten Charlotte eight consecutive times
before the Sting finally broke the streak with a victory in their
only meeting last season.

	   Charlotte caught a break when Comets forward Tina Thompson got
into early foul trouble. Thompson picked up her third foul just
over six minutes into the game and had to sit out the rest of the
first half.

	   Thompson, who scored 26 points in Houston's overtime win over
Cleveland on Saturday, scored 10 on 5-for-12 shooting in 26
minutes.

	   Sheryl Swoopes, the 2000 WNBA MVP who missed last season with a
knee injury, led the Comets with 17 points. But Houston got little
offensive help from anyone else -- the other four starters combined
to score 23 points and the Comets shot just 39 percent for the
game.

	   ``We just can't score, that's our whole problem,'' Houston coach
Van Chancellor said. ``We did a good job on defense, but we
couldn't do anything on offense. It was a long night of
basketball.''
